# Day 61 – Task A-4: Producing the Security Assessment Report | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## From Assessment to Report

Days 59 and 60 completed the Task A-3 assessment execution — seven findings across technical and non-technical controls, three Moderate and four Low, with no High findings. Today, Task A-4 assembles those findings into the Security Assessment Report (SAR): the formal document that the Authorizing Official will use as the primary input to the authorization decision.

The SAR is not a summary of what was tested. It is a structured risk communication document — it tells the AO what the assessor found, how serious each finding is, what the evidence is, and what the AO needs to know to make a defensible risk acceptance decision. Writing it well requires a different skill than conducting the assessment. An assessor who can identify a privilege escalation pathway in an IAM policy still needs to translate that finding into language and structure that enables an AO who may not be deeply technical to understand the risk and make an informed decision.

That translation — from technical finding to risk-informed recommendation — is the core challenge of SAR production.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Task A-4 requires the assessor to prepare the SAR based on the assessment results, have the system owner review for factual accuracy, and deliver the final report to the AO. Today I work through the SAR structure for the OpenMRS assessment — the executive summary, the system and assessment overview sections, the complete findings documentation for all seven findings, the overall risk posture summary, and the assessor's authorization recommendation.

A note on continuity: the original version of today's content described findings (unencrypted RDS snapshots, weak passwords) that were corrected during Task I-1 implementation verification in Days 54-55. The SAR I am producing today reflects the actual assessment findings from Days 59 and 60 — seven findings that emerged despite the thorough implementation work, because the assessment found the gaps the implementation work left behind. This is the realistic picture.

