## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified SAR production today is the distinction between the SAR and the POA&M, and why they serve different audiences.

The SAR is the assessor's document — an independent, evidence-based statement of what was found and how serious it is. The assessor's job in the SAR is to give the AO an accurate, objective picture of the system's security posture. The assessor does not soften findings to make the system owner look good, and does not inflate findings to demonstrate their own rigor. Findings are characterized as they are.

The POA&M is the system owner's document — a commitment to remediate identified gaps within defined timelines. The POA&M responds to the SAR but is owned by the system owner, not the assessor. The AO uses both: the SAR to understand the current state, and the POA&M to understand the planned remediation path and whether the residual risk during that remediation period is acceptable.

Understanding this audience distinction changed how I thought about SAR writing. Every section of the SAR is written for the AO, not for the ISSO or IT Administrator. Technical findings need enough technical specificity that a technically competent reader can verify and remediate them — but they also need clear risk characterization so a non-technical AO can understand why the finding matters.

