#### Finding A-6: Security Awareness Training Has No Downtime Scenario Content

**Control:** AT-2 (Security Awareness Training), CP-3 (Contingency Training)

**Severity:** Low

**Finding Status:** Strengthens existing POA&M items CP-3-01 and CP-2-01

**Description:** The current security awareness training curriculum covers all six required content areas documented in the SSP but does not include any content specifically addressing what clinical staff should do if they cannot access OpenMRS during a shift — how to document patient encounters in downtime mode, how to report the outage, and when to seek additional guidance. The tabletop exercise after-action report identified that clinical staff lack familiarity with manual procedures, and the action item was to complete the clinical downtime procedures document. However, basic awareness guidance could be provided to clinical staff now, independent of the completion of the full downtime procedures document.

**Evidence:** Training curriculum outline reviewed [date]; AT-4 training records reviewed [date]; tabletop after-action report reviewed [date] showing clinical staff unfamiliarity with manual registration.

**Risk:** Low. The technical controls (availability monitoring, backup restoration) are implemented. The gap is in clinical staff preparedness to operate during a downtime event — which affects patient care continuity more than security posture directly.

**Remediation Recommendation:** Add a basic downtime awareness module to the current training curriculum covering: how to recognize and report an EHR system outage; the expectation to use paper-based documentation during downtime; and who to contact for guidance. This basic module should not wait for the full CP-2 clinical downtime procedures document — a 10-minute awareness segment can be developed independently within 30 days.

**POA&M Required:** Update to existing POA&M-CP3-01 — add interim training development as a near-term milestone separate from the full downtime procedures completion.

