## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While drafting the authorization recommendation section today — specifically the framing of conditional authorization versus unconditional authorization — I thought about the **2015 Office of Personnel Management (OPM) breach** and what the authorization record revealed.

Post-breach investigation found that several OPM systems involved in the breach were operating on expired Authorizations to Operate — systems that had either never received a formal ATO or had not completed re-authorization after their previous ATO expired. Congressional testimony and the OIG reports documented that the authorization process had been treated as a checkbox rather than a living risk management activity.

The contrast with what an AO's conditional authorization represents is instructive. A conditional authorization with specific, tracked remediation requirements — remediate Finding A-3 within 15 days, verify and report back — is a risk acceptance with accountability built in. The AO is not saying "this system is perfect." The AO is saying "this system's residual risk is acceptable for operation, provided these specific gaps are closed within these specific timelines, and I will verify they are."

That accountability structure — authorization as an ongoing risk management commitment, not a one-time approval — is what prevents the drift that characterized the OPM authorization situation. The SAR and the conditions it generates are the mechanism that keeps the AO engaged with the system's actual security posture throughout the authorization period, not just at the moment of initial approval.

